title: The artist celebrating the Top End's wild tropical creatures, both animal and human | ABC NEWS
description: A celebration of the wildness of the Northern Territory's creatures, animal and human, has launched at a community art gallery in Darwin. title: Australia's most popular baby names from 2025 revealed | ABC NEWS
description: Every year, each Australian state and territory compiles data from their Births, Deaths and Marriages registries to reveal the most popular names parents picked for their babies. Charlotte, Isla and Amelia reclaimed their status as popular female baby names in 2025, with hundreds of babies given those names across a number of regions. Meanwhile, the latest data on male baby names revealed Oliver and Noah made the top 10 list in every jurisdiction. By Roxanne Fitzgerald for ABC News Northern Territory. title: Trump’s geopolitics undermines AI focus at World Economic Forum | Alan Kohler | ABC NEWS
description: The World Economic Forum initially aimed to focus on artificial intelligence, but discussions were dominated by topics such as Donald Trump, Greenland, NATO, and the rise of China, raising concerns about the stability of the rules-based world order. Global debt has hit a record of over 500 trillion AUD, with 25% of countries now led by populists, predominantly right-wing.  Despite this, the total value of global companies is nearing a record high. This week, market volatility arose as Trump intensified his demands for Greenland and threatened a trade war, leaving investors uncertain. title: Man killed during Minneapolis immigration crackdown | ABC NEWS
description: US federal immigration officers have shot and killed a man in Minneapolis, drawing hundreds of protesters in a city already shaken by a fatal shooting weeks earlier.   The man killed has been identified by family members as Alex Jeffrey Pretti, who was a 37-year-old intensive care nurse in the city.  Department of Homeland Security spokesperson Tricia McLaughlin said in a statement that federal officers were conducting an operation as part of the Trump administration's immigration crackdown and fired "defensive shots" after a man with a handgun approached them and "violently resisted" when officers tried to disarm him.   Earlier, Minneapolis Police Chief Brian O'Hara said police believed the man was a US citizen, and a "lawful gun owner with a permit to carry".   The shooting happened amid widespread daily protests in Minneapolis since the January 7 shooting of 37-year-old Renee Good, who was killed when an Immigration and Customs Enforcement officer fired into her vehicle. title: Police confirm possible sighting of suspected gunman Julian Ingram | ABC NEWS
description: NSW Police have confirmed the first possible sighting of Julian Ingram, who is wanted in connection to the shooting death of three people in Lake Cargelligo on Thursday.   Western Region Commander Assistant Commissioner Andrew Holland said investigators received information overnight about the potential sighting at Mount Hope, an hour north-west of Lake Cargelligo.   "Tactical police are in that location now, carrying out multiple searches in the area," he said.   "We are asking members of the public to exercise extreme caution."   Mr Ingram is accused of killing three people and seriously injuring another in Lake Cargelligo on Thursday afternoon.
